{
    "name": "Watch Officer",
    "type": "npc",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Watch Officer",
            "type": "section",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Gamemastery Guide",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 234",
                        "alt": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 234",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01zq7"
                    },
                    "page": 234
                }
            ],
            "html": "Watch officers are assigned to a certain area within a city or community. Often leading a small team of lower-ranking guards, they patrol those areas to maintain order and enforce laws. Watch officers get the job done, though their methods are not always gentle or kind. Because the watch officer is responsible to their superiors for their area, they sometimes need to make tough decisions between justice and effectiveness.<br/><br/><b><u><a aonid=\"5\" game-obj=\"Skills\" general=\"true\">Recall Knowledge - Humanoid</a></u> (<u><a aonid=\"14\" game-obj=\"Skills\">Society</a></u>)</b>: DC 18"
        },
        {
            "name": "Officers",
            "type": "section",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "name": "Deploying The Watch",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Gamemastery Guide",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "alt": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01zq7"
                            },
                            "page": 232
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "advice_and_rules",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Advice and Rules",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Advice and Rules",
                        "image": "Sidebar_1_AdviceAndRules.png"
                    },
                    "html": "If no guard is present, it takes at least 1\u20132 rounds for a civilian to find a guard to sound an alarm whistle. If a guard was on the scene, they sound the alarm immediately. Reinforcements typically arrive 2\u20133 rounds later."
                },
                {
                    "name": "Jailbreak!",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Gamemastery Guide",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "alt": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01zq7"
                            },
                            "page": 232
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "advice_and_rules",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Advice and Rules",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Advice and Rules",
                        "image": "Sidebar_1_AdviceAndRules.png"
                    },
                    "html": "If a PC or ally gets imprisoned, the group might plot a jailbreak. For a complex jail or penitentiary, this might require use of the <a aonid=\"1221\" game-obj=\"Rules\">infiltration</a> subsystem. With a smaller town or city jail with a simple structure and small staff, it could require just a bit of force. The jailbreak might just be the beginning, leading to additional adventure!"
                },
                {
                    "name": "Raise The Alarm!",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Gamemastery Guide",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "alt": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01zq7"
                            },
                            "page": 232
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "advice_and_rules",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Advice and Rules",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Advice and Rules",
                        "image": "Sidebar_1_AdviceAndRules.png"
                    },
                    "html": "In a settlement with an alarm, brawls or other major disruptions trigger an alarm 1 round after the watch is alerted. Guards start to arrive after about 5 rounds, usually in patrols of 2 or 3 members, with larger groups of 8\u201312 near important locations."
                },
                {
                    "name": "Unusual Misdemeanors",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Gamemastery Guide",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "alt": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01zq7"
                            },
                            "page": 232
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    },
                    "html": "<ul><li>Altering the weather without a permit</li><li>Consuming (or refusing to consume) intoxicating substances on celebration days</li><li>Failing to clean up after animal companions</li><li>Flying within city limits</li><li>Selling potions without a license</li></ul>"
                }
            ],
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Gamemastery Guide",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                        "alt": "Gamemastery Guide pg. 232",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01zq7"
                    },
                    "page": 232
                }
            ],
            "html": "Larger societies rely on those with the authority and the ability to interpret and enforce laws. In good-aligned societies, these officials carry out their duties fairly. In neutral and evil ones, these officials can be harsh and cruel (with an altered alignment to reflect this), imposing severe punishments on those who can't pay for mercy."
        }
    ],
